'''Morten Axboe''' (born 1946) is a Danish archaeologist and curator at the National Museum of Denmark, notable for his study of [[bracteate]]s. Axboe is also known for theorizing a connection between finds of 6th century Scandinavian gold hoards and the [[extreme weather events of 535–536]], as a reacton to the 'dying' sun and the [[fimbulwinter]]-like climate of those years. Gold may have been buried, he suggested, as sacrifices intended to appease the gods.

Axboe has also published on the manufacture of the [[Torslunda plates]] and the making of Migration Period chip-carving ornament.

In 2007 he obtained his [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]] with his dissertation ''Brakteatstudier'' (Studies in Gold Bracteates). Like many of his papers, this book is accessible on Academia.edu.

