'''Niels Thomasius Neergaard''' (27 June 1854 &ndash; 2 September 1936) was a Danish [[historian]] and [[political figure]], a member of the [[Liberalism|Liberal]] [[Moderate Venstre (Denmark)|Moderate Venstre]] and since 1910 of [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]]. He served as [[Council President of Denmark]] between 1908 and 1909 as head of the [[Cabinet of Neergaard I]] and as both [[Prime minister of Denmark]] and [[Finance Minister of Denmark|Finance Minister]] from 5 May 1920 to 23 April 1924, leading the [[Cabinet of Neergaard II]] and [[Cabinet of Neergaard III|III]]. His last cabinet office was as [[Finance Minister of Denmark|Finance Minister]] (14 December 1926 &ndash; 30 April 1929). 

==Biography==
He was born on 27 June 1854.

Neergaard's greatest challenges as a politician were as prime minister and finance minister after the [[Easter Crisis of 1920]], organizing the return of [[Southern Jutland|South Jutland]] to Danish rule and having to deal with the economic crisis brought on by [[World War I]].<ref name=Skou>Skou, Kaare R. (2005). ''Dansk politik A-Å'' {{da icon}}. Aschehoug, pp. 491-92. {{ISBN|87-11-11652-8}}.</ref> He also had a significant influence on the content of the [[Constitution of Denmark|Constitution of 1915]].<ref name=Skou/>

Neergaard's largest work as a historian, ''Under junigrundloven'' (1892-1916), is still considered the primary work on Danish politics 1848-66.<ref name=Skou/> In addition to his political activities and work as a historian he also dealt with journalism, and in 1884 he founded a cultural and [[literary magazine]], ''[[Tilskueren]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter Brooker|author2=Sascha Bru|author3=Andrew Thacker|author4=Christian Weikop|title=The Oxford Critical and Cultural History of Modernist Magazines: Europe 1880 - 1940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bvsfioiQ8k8C&pg=PA622|accessdate=9 May 2015|date=19 May 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-965958-6|page=622}}</ref>

He died on 2 September 1936.

