[[File:East Slavic tribes peoples 8th 9th century.jpg|right|thumb|250px|European territory inhabited by [[West Slavs]] and [[East Slavs]] circa 700-850 AD.]]
'''White Croats''' ({{lang-hr|Bijeli Hrvati}}, {{lang-pl|Biali Chorwaci}}, {{lang-cz|Bílí Chorvati}}, {{lang-ua|Білі хорвати}} [[Romanization of Ukrainian|tr.]] {{lang|uk-Latn|Bili Khorvaty}}) were a group of [[Slavs|Slavic]] tribes who lived among other [[West Slavs|West]] and [[East Slavs|East]] Slavic tribes in the area of [[Bohemia]], [[Lesser Poland]], [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] (north of [[Carpathian Mountains]]) and modern-day [[Western Ukraine]].{{sfn|Subtelny|2009|p=57}}{{sfn|Magocsi|2010|p=49}}{{sfn|Dzino|2010|pp=113, 21}} They were documented primarily by foreign medieval authors and managed to preserve their ethnic name until the early 20th century, primarily in Lesser Poland. It is considered that they got assimilated into Czech, Polish and Ukrainian ethnos,{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=131}} and are one of the predecessors of the [[Rusyns|Rusyn]] people.{{sfn|Magocsi|1995}}{{sfn|Magocsi|2005|p=5}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=78}} In the 7th century, some White Croats migrated from their homeland [[White Croatia]] to the territory of modern-day [[Croatia]], forming the ancestors of the South Slavic ethnic group of [[Croats]].

==Origin==
It is generally believed that the [[Name of Croatia|Croatian ethnonym]] - ''Hrvat''/''Horvat''/''Harvat'' - etymologically is not of Slavic origin, but a borrowing from [[Iranian languages]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=95}}{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=115, 168, 444}} It is considered that the ethnonym ''Hrvat'' is first attested on the two [[Tanais Tablets]], found in the Greek colony of [[Tanais]] in the late 2nd and early 3rd century AD, at the time when the colony was surrounded by Iranian-speaking [[Sarmatians]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=262}} The first Iranian tribes who lived on the shores of the [[Sea of Azov]] were [[Scythians]], who arrived there c. 7th century BCE.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=100–101}} Around the 6th century BCE the Sarmatians began their migration westwards, gradually subordinating the Scythians by the 2nd-century BCE.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=101–102}} During this period there was substantial cultural and [[Proto-Slavic borrowings#Slavic and Iranian|linguistic]] contact between the [[Early Slavs]] and [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]]s,{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=102}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=42–54}} and in this environment were formed [[Antes (people)|Antes]].{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=115, 168}}

Antes were Slavic people who lived in that area and to the West between [[Dniester]] and [[Dnieper]] from the 4th until the 7th century.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=110}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=84}} It is thought that White Croats were part of the Antes tribal polity who migrated to Galicia in the 3rd-4th century, under pressure by invading [[Huns]] and [[Goths]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=115–116}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=84–87}}{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=444, 451, 501, 516}} They lived there until the Antes were attacked by the [[Pannonian Avars]] in 560, and the polity was finally destroyed in 602 by the same Avars.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=111}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=141}} This resulted with breaking Croatian tribal unity into several groups, in [[Prykarpattia]] ([[Western Ukraine]]), in [[Silesia]] and the lower course of the [[Vistula]] river ([[Lesser Poland]]), and Eastern [[Czech Republic]].{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=168, 444, 451}} The early Croats' migration to [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] (during the reign of [[Heraclius]] 610-641) can thus be seen as a continuation of the previous war between the Antes and Avars.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=141}} The epithet "white" for the Croats and their homeland is related to the use of colors for [[Cardinal direction#Northern Eurasia|cardinal directions]] among Eurasian people. That is, it meant "Western Croats", in comparison to lands where they lived before. The epithet "great" signified an "old, ancient" or "former" homeland,{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=84–88}} for the Croats when they were new arrivals in the Roman province of Dalmatia.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=122–125}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=27}}{{sfn|Kim|2013|pp=146, 262}}

There is a dispute among Slavic scholars as to whether the White Croats were of Irano-[[Alans|Alanic]], West Slavic, or East Slavic origin.{{sfn|Magocsi|1983|p=49}}{{sfn|Magocsi|2002|p=4}}{{sfn|Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.|1991|pp=53, 56}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=58}} Some scholars linguistically and archaeologically draw parallels between White Croats and Slavs, and the [[Carpi (people)|Carpi]], who previously lived in the territory of Carpathian Mountains.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=115–116}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=87–89}} Whether the early Croats were Slavs who had taken a name of Iranian origin, or whether they were ruled by a Sarmatian elite and/or were slavicized Sarmatians, cannot be resolved. The possibility of Irano-Sarmatian elements among, or influences upon, early Croatian ethnogenesis cannot be entirely excluded.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=305–306}}{{sfn|Dzino|2010|pp=113, 21}}{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=12}}{{sfn|Norris|1993|p=15}}

[[File:Ptolemaic map Scythia 1598.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Ptolemaic map of Scythia 1598; the ''Horinei'' are mentioned below [[Amazons]].]]
Any mention of the Croats before the 9th century is uncertain, and there were several loose attempts at tracing; ''Struhates'' and ''Auhates'' by [[Herodotus]], [[Chatti]] and [[Chattuarii]] by [[Strabo]], ''Choatræ'' and ''Arivates'' by [[Pliny the Elder]],{{sfn|Marčinko|2000|p=318–319, 433}} ''Horites'' by [[Orosius]] in 418 AD,{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=127}} and the ''Harus'' (original form ''Hrws'',{{sfn|Danylenko|2004|pp=1–32}} some read ''Hrwts'';{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=13}} ''Hros'', ''Hrus'') at the Sea of Azov, near mythical [[Amazons]],{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=88, 91–92}} mentioned by [[Zacharias Rhetor]] in 550 AD.{{sfn|Danylenko|2004|pp=1–32}} The ''Hros'' some relate to the [[Rus (name)|ethnonym]] of the [[Rus' people]].{{sfn|Danylenko|2004|pp=1–32}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=87–95}}

==History==

===Middle Ages===
[[Nestor the Chronicler]] in his ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' (12th century) mentions the White Croats, calling them ''Horvate Belii'' or ''Hrovate Belii'', the name depending upon which manuscript of his is referred to: "''Over a long period the Slavs settled beside the [[Danube]], where the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] and [[Bulgaria]]n lands now lie. From among these Slavs, parties scattered throughout the country and were known by appropriate names, according to the places where they settled. Thus some came and settled by the river [[Morava (river)|Morava]], and were named [[Moravians (tribe)|Moravians]], while others were called [[Czechs]]. Among these same Slavs are included the White Croats, the [[White Serbia|Serbs]], and the [[Carantanians|Carinthians]]. For when the Vlakhs (Romans) attacked the Danubian Slavs, settled among them, and did them violence, the latter came and made their homes by the [[Vistula]], and were then called Lyakhs ([[Lendians]] or [[Lechites]]). Of these same Lyakhs some were called [[Polans (western)|Polyanians]], some Lutichians, some [[Masovians|Mazovians]], and still others [[Pomeranians (Slavic tribe)|Pomorians]]''".{{sfn|Cross, Sherbowitz-Wetzor|1953|p=53}}

Most what is known about the early history of White Croats comes from the work by the Byzantine emperor [[Constantine VII]], ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'' (10th century).{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=116–117}} In the 30th chapter, "The Story of the Province of Dalmatia" Constantine wrote: {{quote|"''The Croats at that time were dwelling beyond Bagibareia (usually considered to be [[Bavaria]]), where the Belocroats are now. From them split off a family, namely of five brothers, Kloukas and Lobelos and Kosentzis and Mouchlo and Chrobatos, and two sisters, Touga and Bouga, who came with their folk to Dalmatia and found this land under the rule of the Avars. After they had fought one another for some years, the Croats prevailed and killed some of the Avars and the remainder they compelled to be subject to them... The rest of the Croats stayed over near Francia, and are now called the Belocroats, that is, the White Croats, and have their own archon; they are subject to [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto]], the great king of Francia, which is also Saxony, and are unbaptized, and intermarry and are friendly with the Turks. From the Croats who came to Dalmatia, a part split off and took rule of [[Praetorian prefecture of Illyricum|Illyricum]] and [[Pannonia]]. They too had an independent archon, who would maintain friendly contact, though through envoys only, with the archon of Croatia... From that time they remained independent and autonomous, and they requested holy baptism from Rome, and bishops were sent and baptized them in the time of their Archon [[Porga of Croatia|Porinos]]''".{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=111–122}}}}

The migration probably happened in the period of the Slavic uprising led by [[Samo]] against the Pannonian Avars in 632,{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=217}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=62}} and 635-641 when were defeated by [[Kubrat]] of the [[Bulgars]].{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=182}} The White Croats could have been the neighbors of the Franks as early as 846 or 869 when Bohemia was under the control of Eastern Francia. Otto I ruled the [[Moravians (tribe)|Moravians]] only from 950, and the White Croats were also part of the Moravian state, at least from 929.{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=120}} In the 31st chapter, "Of the Croats and of the Country They Now Dwell in" Constantine wrote: {{quote|"''These same Croats arrived as refugees to the emperor of the Romaioi Heraclius before the Serbs came as refugees to the same Emperor Heraclius, at that time when the Avars had fought and expelled from those parts the Romani... Now, by the command of the Emperor Heraclius, these same Croats fought and expelled the Avars from those parts, and, by mandate of Heraclius the emperor they settled down in that same country of the Avars, where they now dwell. These same Croats had the father of [[Porga of Croatia|Porga]] for their archon at that time... (It should be known) that ancient Croatia, also called "white", is still unbaptized to this day, as are also its neighboring Serbs. They muster fewer horsemen as well as fewer foot than baptized Croatia, because they are constantly plundered by the [[Franks]] and [[Hungarians|Turks]] and [[Pechenegs]]. Nor do they have either sagēnai or [[Kondura (ship)|kondourai]] or merchant ships, because they live far away from sea; it takes 30 days of travel from the place where they live to the sea. The sea to which they come down to after 30 days, is that which is called [[Black Sea|dark]]''".{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=49, 54, 83, 88}}}}

According to this chapter, the Pechenegs and Hungarians were neighbours of the White Croats to the east in the second half of the 9th century. In that time Franks plundered Moravia, and White Croatia was probably a part of the [[Great Moravia]].{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=89}} A similar story to the 30th chapter is mentioned in the work by [[Thomas the Archdeacon]], ''[[Historia Salonitana]]'' (13th century), where he recounts how seven or eight tribes of nobles, which he called ''Lingones'', arrived from present-day [[Poland]] and settled in Croatia under Totila's leadership.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} According to the Archdeacon, they were called Goths, but also Slavs, depending on the personal names of those who came from Poland or the Czech lands.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=129–130}} Some scholars consider ''Lingones'' to be a distortion of the name for the Polish tribe of Lendians.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=130}}

[[Alfred the Great]] in his ''Geography of Europe'' (888–893) relying on [[Paulus Orosius|Orosius]], recorded that, "''To the north-east of the Moravians are the Dalamensae; east of the Dalamensians are the Horithi (Choroti, Choriti;{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=52}} Croats), and north of the Dalamensians are the Servians (Serbs); to the west also are the [[Silesians]]. To the north of the Horiti is [[Mazovia]], and north of Mazovia are the Sarmatians, as far as the [[Riphean Mountains]]''".{{sfn|Ingram|1807|p=72}} The initial north-east position was probably wrongly transcribed, as a north-west position agrees with other sources on the location of the Croats on the [[Oder]] and Vistula Rivers.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=210}}

Nestor described how many East Slavic tribes of "''...the [[Polans (eastern)|Polyanians]], the [[Drevlians|Derevlians]], the [[Severians]], the [[Radimichs|Radimichians]], and the Croats lived at peace''".{{sfn|Cross, Sherbowitz-Wetzor|1953|p=56}} In 904-907, "''Leaving [[Igor of Kiev|Igor]] (914–945) in [[Kiev]], [[Oleg of Novgorod|Oleg]] (879–912) attacked the Greeks. He took with him a multitude of Varangians, Slavs, Chuds, [[Krivichs|Krivichians]], Merians, Polyanians, Severians, Derevlians, Radimichians, Croats, [[Dulebes|Dulebians]], and [[Tivertsi|Tivercians]], who are pagans. All these tribes are known as Great [[Scythia]] by the Greeks. With this entire force, Oleg sallied forth by horse and by ship, and the number of his vessels was two thousand''".{{sfn|Cross, Sherbowitz-Wetzor|1953|p=64}} The list indicates that the closest tribal neighbours were Tivertsti and Dulebes-[[Volhynians]].{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=69}} After [[Vladimir the Great]] (980–1015) conquered several Slavic tribes and cities to the West,{{sfn|Magocsi|2002|p=4}} in 992 he "''attacked the Croats. When he had returned from the Croatian War, the Pechenegs arrived on the opposite side of the Dnieper''".{{sfn|Cross, Sherbowitz-Wetzor|1953|p=119}} Since then those Croats became part of [[Kievan Rus]], and aren't mentioned anymore in Russian Chronicles.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=144}}{{sfn|Magocsi|2002|p=4}} It seems that Croatian tribes who lived in the area of [[Bukovina]] and Galicia were conquered because inhibited Kievan Rus free access to the Vistula river,{{sfn|Hanak|2013|p=32}} did not want to submit to Kievan centralism and accept Christianity.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=123}} After the attack, since 1124 the territory became part of [[Principality of Halych]].{{sfn|Korčinskij|2000|p=113}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=39}}

Polish chronicler [[Wincenty Kadłubek]] in his ''[[Chronica seu originale regum et principum Poloniae|Chronica Polonorum]]'' (12-13th century) recounted that [[Bolesław I the Brave]] (992 to 1025) conquered some "''Hunnos seu Hungaros, Cravatios et Mardos, gentem validam, suo mancipavit imperio''".{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=144}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=74}} The occurrence of the Croatian name among the toponyms, indicates that the Croatia near the Vistula river corresponded with the later territory of [[Lesser Poland]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=147}}

Many Croats also lived in the territory of Bohemia. The Prague Charter from 1086 AD (actually with data from 973) mentions that on the northeastern frontier of the Prague diocese lived "''Psouane, Chrouati et altera Chrowati, Zlasane...''".{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=148}} They were also probably settled east of [[Zlicans]] and west of [[Moravians (tribe)|Moravians]] having significant territory around the [[Elbe]] river,{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=428}} while the others were present along the upper Vistula in Poland.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=149}} Some scholars located these Czech Croats within the territory of present-day [[Chrudim]], [[Hradec Králové]], [[Libice nad Cidlinou|Libice]] and [[Kłodzko]].{{sfn|Vach|2006 (1949)|p=239}}{{sfn|Widajewicz|2006 (1949)|p=267–268}} Vach argued that they had the most developed techniques of building fortifications among the Czech Slavs.{{sfn|Vach|2006 (1949)|p=240–242}} Many scholars consider that the [[Slavník dynasty]], which competed with the [[Přemyslid dynasty]] for control over Bohemia (and eventually succumbed to them) and partly controlled Croats territory,{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=431}} was of White Croat origin. According to a legend about [[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Bohemia|Wenceslaus I]], his mother [[Drahomíra]] fled in exile to ''Xorvaty''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=150}}{{sfn|Vach|2006 (1949)|p=255–256}} After the Slavník dynasty's main Gord (fortified settlement) Libice was destroyed in 995, the White Croats aren't mentioned anymore in that territory.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=151}}

[[Thietmar of Merseburg]] recorded in 981 toponym ''Chrvuati vicus'' (also later recorded in 11th-14th century), which is present-day [[Großkorbetha]], between [[Halle (Saale)|Halle]] and [[Merseburg]] in [[Saxony-Anhalt]], Germany.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=158}} The ''Chruuati'' (901) and ''Chruuati'' (981) near Halle.{{sfn|Marčinko|2000|p=183}} In charter by [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II]] is recorded ''Chruazzis'' (1012), by [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry III]] as ''Churbate'' (1055), by [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] as ''Grawat'' (also ''Curewate'', 1086). This settlement today is Korbetha on river [[Saale]], near [[Weißenfels]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=158}}

In the 10th-12th centuries Croatian name can be often found in the territory of [[March of Carinthia|March]] and [[Duchy of Carinthia|Duchy]] of Carinthia, as well [[March of Styria|March]] and [[Duchy of Styria|Duchy]] of Styria.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=161–167}} In 954, Otto I in his charter mentions [[župa]] ''Croat'' - "''hobas duas proorietatis nostrae in loco Zuric as in pago Crouuati et in ministerio Hartuuigi''",{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=161}} and again in 961 ''pago Crauuati''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=161–162}} The ''pago Chruuat'' is also mentioned by [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto II]] (979), and ''pago Croudi'' by [[Otto III, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto III]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=162}}

In the 10th century, Arab historian [[Al-Masudi]] in his work ''[[The Meadows of Gold]]'' mentioned ''Harwātin'' or ''Khurwātīn'', between Moravians, Chezchs and [[Saxons]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=211}}{{sfn|Zimonyi|2015|pp=295, 319}} In the geography book ''[[Hudud al-'Alam]]'' in the area of Slavs is mentioned their two capital cities, ''Wabnit'' (actually ''Wāntit'', considered Antes{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=212–213}}), the first city East of Slavs, and ''Hurdāb'', a big city where rulers reside on river ''Rūtā'' (probably [[Prut]]).{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=211–212}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=161}} In the chronicles of the time word ''šahr'' meant "country, state, city" - thus ''Hurdāb'' represented Croats.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=212}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=32}} In work by [[Abu Saʿīd Gardēzī]] it is mentioned as ''ʒ(h)-rāwat''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=212}} [[Ahmad ibn Rustah]] recounts that the land of Pechenegs is ten days away from the Slavs, and that the city in which lives ''Swntblk'' ([[Svatopluk I of Moravia|Svatopluk]]) is called ''ʒ-r-wāb'' (''Džervab'' > ''Hrwat''), where every month Slavs do three-day long trade fair.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=212–213}} ''Swntblk'' is called "king of kings", has riding horses, sturdy armor, eats mare's milk, and is more important than ''Subanj'' (considered Slavic title [[župan]]), who is his deputy.{{sfn|Vernadsky|2008 (1935)|p=262–263}} [[George Vernadsky]] considered these details as evidence of Alanic and Eurasian nomadic origin of the ruling caste among those Slavs.{{sfn|Vernadsky|2008 (1935)|p=262–263}} In the Hebrew book ''[[Josippon]]'' are listed four Slavic ethnic names from [[Venice]] to [[Saxony]]; ''Mwr.wh'' (Moravians), ''Krw.tj'' (Croats), ''Swrbjn'' ([[Sorbs (tribe)|Sorbs]]), ''Lwcnj''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=214}} Those Croats are probably those who were located in Bohemia.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=214}}

White Croats seemingly were not recorded by the [[Bavarian Geographer]], however, some scholars assumed that the unknown ''Sittici'' ("a region with many peoples and heavily fortified cities") and ''Stadici'' ("an infinite population with 516 gords") were part of the Carpathian Croats tribal polity,{{sfn|Koncha|2012|p=17}} or the Croats were part of this unknown tribal designation in [[Prykarpattia]].{{sfn|Kugutjak|2017|p=26}}{{sfn|Tomenčuk|2017|p=32}} Others in unknown ''Lupiglaa'' (with 30 gords) saw Czech Croats and Zlicans.{{sfn|Łowmiański|2013 (1958)|p=120}}

It is considered that the Czech-Polish Croatian tribes were related to the Croatian tribes from [[Carpathian Ruthenia|Zakarpattia]] and Prykarpattia in Ukraine.{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=168, 444, 451}}{{sfn|Budak|2018|p=93}} They became separated during the [[migration period]] and seemingly formed one large Proto-Slavic tribe.{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=168, 444, 451, 501, 516}} It is theorized that the migration of those (White) Croatian tribes in the 7th century was the second and final Slavic migratory wave to the [[Balkans]],{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=217}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=62}}{{sfn|Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.|1991|pp=53, 56}} which is related to the thesis by [[Bogo Grafenauer]] about the double migration of Slavs.{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=97}} According to this thesis, although it is possible that some Croatian tribes were present among Slavs in the first Slavic-Avar wave in the 6th century, it is argued that the Croatian migration in the second wave probably was not equally numerous to make a significant common-linguistical influence,{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=62}}{{sfn|Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.|1991|pp=53, 56}} while others considered they arrived in a significantly larger number.{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=176, 446, 460}} [[Zdenko Vinski]] and [[:ru:Седов, Валентин Васильевич|V. V. Sedov]] argued that the double migration thesis is supported by the rare findings of objects and ceramics of [[Prague-Korchak culture]] on the territory of Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Serbia which were dated to the end of 6th and beginning of the 7th century (indicating first wave Slavs), and did not make a continuity with Slavic archaeological findings from the 8th-9th century, indicating assimilation.{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=169, 175–176, 444, 460}} The Croatian tribes are also seen as a warrior group who assimilated into already present Slavs.{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=62}} In the territory of present-day Croatia they also gradually assimilated with the Pre-Slavic population because archaeology indicates a significant continuity of [[late antiquity]] population which have partially withdrawn to the mountains, coastal cities and islands.{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=104–105}}{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=446}}

====Archeology====
By the 7th century White Croats had established and fortified [[Horod]]s ([[Gord (archaeology)|Gord]]), which became a commerce and trade centers.{{sfn|Magocsi|2002|p=4}} Galicia was an important geographical location because it connected via an overland route Kiev in the East with [[Krakow]], [[Buda]], [[Prague]] and other cities in the West, as well as northwest to the [[Baltic Sea]] and southeast to the [[Black Sea]].{{sfn|Magocsi|2002|p=4}} Along these routes were founded the settlements of [[Przemyśl]], [[Zvenyhorod]], [[Terebovlia]], [[Halych]], and [[Uzhhorod]], of which the last was ruled by a mythical ruler [[Laborec (ruler)|Laborec]].{{sfn|Magocsi|2002|p=4}}{{sfn|Magocsi|2005|p=5}} According to research by Sedov in 1979, all early mentions of Croatian ethnonym are in the areas where ceramics of [[Penkovka culture|Prague-Penkovka culture]] were found. It originated in the area between [[Dniester]] and [[Dnieper]], and later expanded to the West, and its bearers were the Antes tribes.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=130–134}} A. V. Majorov criticized Sedov's consideration, which almost exclusively related White Croats with Penkovka culture and the Antes, because the territory White Croats inhabited in the middle and upper Dniester and the upper Vistula was part of [[Prague-Korchak culture]] related to [[Sclaveni]] which was characteristic for the [[Kurgan]]-type of burial which was also found in the upper Elbe territory where lived the Czech Croats.{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=85, 131, 168}} They were representatives of both these archaeological cultures and possibly formed before them at the least late 4th or during the 5th century in the area of the intertwining of these cultures around the Dniester basin.{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=85–86, 168}}

[[File:Городище давньоруське..JPG|right|thumb|250px|Mound of the [[Grad (Slavic settlement)|gord]] [[Stilsko]].]]
Archaeological excavations held between 1981-1995 by Ukrainian archaeologist and historian Orest Korčinski and others who researched Early Middle Age Gords in [[Prykarpattia]] and Western [[Podolia]] dated between 9th-11th century found that fortified Gords with a range of 0.2 ha made 65%, those of 2 ha 20%, and more than 2 ha 15% in that region.{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=34–35}} There were 35 Gords, including big Gords like Revno, Stilsko, [[Zhydachiv]], Kotorin complex, Klyuchi, Stuponica, [[Krylos]], Pidhorodyshche, Terebovlia, Ganachivka, Solonsko among others.{{sfn|Korčinskij|2000|p=113–120}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=38–39}} Only 12 of them survived until the 14th century.{{sfn|Korčinskij|2000|p=120}} Korčinski's excavation revealed a Gord (since 2008 dated in between 8th-9th century{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2008)|p=210–212}}) of unusually big dimension with a surface of 250 ha, including a fortress of 15 ha, defensive line of 10 km,{{sfn|Korčinskij|2004|p=2}} located on river Kolodnitsa (connected to most important river in the region, Dniester{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2008)|p=212}}) between current village [[Stilsko]] and [[Lviv]] which Ukrainian archaeologists attribute to the White Croats.{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006 (1991)|p=68–71}} In its vicinity were also found some of the only examples of a pre-Christian period cult building among Slavs,{{sfn|Korčinskij|2004|p=2–7}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2008)|p=220–221}} for one of which Korčinski assumed a possible connection with the medieval descriptions of a temple dedicated to the deity [[Deities of Slavic religion#Sun-god and moon-god|Hors]].{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006 (1991)|p=71}} Until 2008 near Stilsko have been found more than 50 settlements of open type dated between 8th-10th century,{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2008)|p=212}} as well around 200 [[Tumulus|burial mounds]].{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2008)|p=221}} It indicates a high economic, demographic, defense and political organization,{{sfn|Korčinskij|2006 (1991)|p=70}} and is argued to have been a capital of Eastern (Carpathian) Croats.{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2008)|p=212}} According to archaeological material, by the end of 10th and beginning of 11th century it ceased to exist for now unknown reasons and the fire traces of possible enemy invasion are not considered as sufficient consequence.{{sfn|Korčinskij|2013 (2007)|p=264}} Excavations of many Slavic [[Kurgan]]s and tombs in the Carpathian Mountains in the 1930s and 1960s were also attributed to the White Croats.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=113}} Compared to other East Slavic tribes, the area of the Croats stands out because of very present tiled tombs,{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=502}} and in the 11th and 13th century their appearance in Western Dnieper region is attributed to the Croats, and sometimes [[Tivertsi]].{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=118}} Scholars attribute to the Croats also the forts West and North of river [[Prut]] and in Northern [[Bukovina]]; the Revno, Červona Dibrova, Kodin, Bila, Široka Poljana, Klokučka, Grobnica, Červenovo, Orosijevo, Červone, [[Ungvár]].{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=119}} In the territory of Czech Republic, a significant number of graves with kurgans dated 8th-10th century have been found around the Elbe river where was the presumed territory by the White Croats and Zlicans, as well among Dulebes in the South, and Moravians in the East.{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=430, 435–437}}

====Religion====
Croatian tribes were like other Slavs [[Slavic mythology|polytheists]] - [[Paganism|pagans]].{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=143}} Their worldview intertwined with worship of power and war, to which raised places of worship, and demolished those of others.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=144, 146}} These worships were in contrast to [[Christianity]], and conflict when Christianism became official ideology among the Slavs.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=144}} The White Croats at the earliest historical sources are mentioned as pagans, and they were similar to the inhabitants of [[Kievan Rus']] who also received Christianity late (988).{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=145, 147}} Slavs often related places of worship with the natural environment, like hills, forests, and water.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=145}} Some argue that Przemyśl was their as well as Slavic bishops capital in the 9th-century because there were uncovered foundations of a round chapel and palace made of cut stone.{{sfn|Struk|1993|p=841}} According to Nestor, [[Vladimir the Great]] in 980 raised on a hill near his fort [[pantheon (religion)|pantheon]] of Slavic gods; [[Perun]], [[Deities of Slavic religion#Sun-god and moon-god|Hors]], [[Dažbog]], [[Stribog]], [[Simargl]], and [[Mokosh]],{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=123}} but as he converted to Christianity in 988 one of the probable reasons Vladimir attacked Croats in 992 was because they didn't want to abandon their old beliefs and accept Christianity.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=123}} Some scholars derived Croatian ethnonym from the Iranian word for Sun - ''[[Hvare-khshaeta|hvar]]''.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=59}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=92}} Paščenko argued possibility that in the ethnonym of the Croats could be seen archaic religion and mythology - the worship of the Slavic [[solar deity]] Hors (Sun, heavenly fire, force, war{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=79}}), which is of Iranian origin.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=67–82, 109–111}}

====Origo gentis and etymology====
The legend about five brothers and two sisters recorded in Constantine VII's work ''De Administrando Imperio'' was probably part of an oral tradition,{{sfn|Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.|1991|pp=53, 56}} which contradicts the role of [[Heraclius]] in the arrival of Croats to Dalmatia.{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=95}} It is similar to other medieval ''origo gentis'' stories (see for e.g. ''[[Origo Gentis Langobardorum]]''),{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=95}} and some consider it has the same source as the story of [[Bulgars]] recorded by [[Theophanes the Confessor]] in which the Bulgars subjugated [[Seven Slavic tribes]].{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=89}} In this legend is also possibly reflected a migration of seven tribes.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=222}} Curiously, Croats are seemingly the only Slavic people who had a [[saga]] about the period of their migration.{{sfn|Alimov|2015|pp=142}} Also, compared to other medieval stories none of them mentions female personalities, which could indicate a different social organization or different tribes who joined the Croats.{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=97}} For example, [[Henryk Łowmiański]] considered the [[Mazovians]], Dulebes, Croats and [[Veleti]] among the oldest Slavic tribes because Mazovians ethnonym was often related to [[Amazons]] (''-maz-'') while the land of women in North Europe was mentioned by [[Paul the Deacon]], [[Alfred the Great]], as well women's city West of Russian lands by [[Ibrahim ibn Yaqub]].{{sfn|Sedov|2013|p=481}} Another vagueness is a reason and meaning that one of the brothers had a Croatian ethnonym as a name, perhaps indicating he was more important than the other brothers or that the Croats were only one identity among others with which the Adriatic Croats tried to bring legitimacy to the Croatian Kingdom.{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=97}}

The origin of the names of five brothers and two sisters are a matter of dispute. They are often considered to be of non-Slavic origin,{{sfn|Van Antwerp Fine, Jr.|1991|pp=53, 56}} and genuine names, as the anonymous Slavic narrator (probably a Croat) couldn't invent the non-Slavic names of their ancestors in the 9th century.{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=114}} [[J.J. Mikkola]] considered them to be of [[Turkic language|Turkic]] origin,{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126–127}}{{sfn|Margetić|2001|p=32}} Vladimir Košćak of possible Iranian-Alanic origin,{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126, 218}} while Alemko Gluhak saw parallels in Slavic [[Old Prussian language|Old Prussian]] and [[Baltic languages|Baltic]] languages.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=218–221}} [[Henri Grégoire (historian)|Henri Grégoire]] rejected Turkic origin, and related them to Slavic place names which previously were part of White Croatia.{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=93}} According to Gluhak, names Kloukas, Lobelos, Kosentzes and possibly Mouchlo don't seem to be part of Scythian or Alanic name directory.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=218}} Josip Modestin connected their names to toponyms from [[Lika]], where early Croats settled.{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}}

Kloukas; has Greek suffix "-as", thus the root ''Klouk-'' has several derivations; Mikkola considered Turkic ''Külük'', while Tadeusz Lewicki Slavic ''Kuluk'' and ''Kluka''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126}} Grégoire related it with cities [[Cracow]] or [[Głogów]].{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=93}} Modestin related it to village Kukljić.{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}} Gluhak noted several Prussian and [[Latvian language|Latvian]] personal names and toponyms with root *''klauk-'', which relates to sound-writing verbs *''klukati'' (peck) and *''klokotati'' (gurgle).{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=218}} The first mentioned king of the Alans was named Kuluk (c. 51-78 AD).<ref>[http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsEurope/BarbarianAlans.htm Alans (Alani / Geloni)]</ref>

Lobelos; Mikkola considered it a name of uncertain Avar ruler.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126}} Osman Karatay considered common Slavic shift ''Lobel'' < ''Alpel'' (as in ''Lab'' < ''Elbe'').{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=92}} Grégoire related it with city [[Lublin]].{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=93}} Modestin related it to [[Lovinac]].{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}} Gluhak noted many Baltic personal names with root *''lab-'' and *''lob-'' e.g. Labelle, Labulis, Labal, Lobal, which derive from *''lab-'' (good) or ''lobas'' (bays, ravine, valley).{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=219}}

Kosentzis; Mikkola considered Turkic suffix "-či", and derived it from Turkic ''koš'' (camp), ''košun'' (army).{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126}} Grégoire related it with city [[Košice]].{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=93}} Modestin related it to [[Kosinj]].{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}} Many scholars consider relation with Old-Slavic title word *''kosez'' or *''kasez'', that meant social class members who freely elected the [[Knyaz|knez]] of Carantania (658–828). In the 9th century they became nobles, and their tradition preserved until the 16th century. There were many toponyms with the title in Slovenia, but also in [[Lika]] in Croatia.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=127}} Gluhak also noted Baltic names with root *''kas-'' which probably derives from ''kàsti'' (dig), and [[Thracian language|Thracian]] ''Kossintes'', ''Cosintos'', ''Cositon''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=128–129}}

Mouchlo; Mikkola related it to the name of 6th century Hunnic ([[Bulgar]]{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=92}} or [[Kutrigurs|Kutrigur]]{{sfn|Golden|1990|p=99}}) ruler Mougel/Mouâgeris.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126}} Modestin related it to Mohljić.{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}} Gluhak noted [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]] ''muklus'' and Latvian ''muka'' which refer to the mud and marshes, and Prussian names e.g. Mokil, Mokyne.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=220}} There existed Antes king with similar name [[Musokios|Musokios/Musocius]].

Chrobatos; read as Hrovatos, is generally considered to represent Croatian ethnonym ''Hrvat/Horvat'', and the Croatian tribe.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=222}} Some scholars like [[J. B. Bury]] related it with the Turkic name of the Bulgars khan [[Kubrat]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}}{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=86–91}} This etymology is problematic, beside from historical viewpont, as in all forms of Kubrat's name, the letter "r" is third consonant.{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=86–91}}

Touga; Mikkola related it with male Turkic name ''Tugai''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126}} Modestin related it to the Tugomirići, one of the Croatian "twelve noble tribes" described in the [[Pacta conventa (Croatia)|Pacta conventa]] and [[Supetar Cartulary]].{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}} Gluhak noted [[Old Norse]]-[[Germanic languages|Germanic]] *''touga'' (fog, darkness), which meaning wouldn't be much different from other names with Baltic derivation.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=221}}

Bouga; Mikkola related it with male Turkic name ''Buga'', while Lewicki noted Turkic name of Hun ''Bokhas'', Peceneg ''Bogas'', and two generals of Arabian kalifs, ''Bogaj''.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=126–127}} Grégoire related it with the [[Bug River]].{{sfn|Karatay|2003|p=93}} Modestin related it to Bužani (probably related to [[Buzhans]]), medieval Croatian tribe.{{sfn|Gluhak|2000|p=21}} Gluhak noted Proto-Slavic word *''buga'' which in Slavic languages mean "swamp" like places, and the river Bug itself derive from.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=221}}

[[Porga of Croatia|Porga]] from 31st chapter according to Živković derives from Iranian ''pouru-gâo'', "rich in cattle".{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=54}} However, in the 30th chapter, it is named Porin, and recently Milošević, Alimov, and Budak supported a thesis which considered these names as two variants of the Slavic deity [[Perun]], as a heavenly ruler and not an actual secular ruler.{{sfn|Alimov|2015|pp=141–164}}{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=95–96}}

===Modern era===
Polish writer Kazimierz Władysław Wóycicki released work ''Pieśni ludu Białochrobatów, Mazurów i Rusi z nad Bugu'' in 1836.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=121–122}} In 1861, in the statistical data about population in [[Volhynia]] governorship released by Mikhail Lebedkin, were counted Horvati with 17,228 people.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=145}}{{sfn|Zimonyi|2015|pp=295, 319}}

According to some American documents from the beginning of the 20th century, Polish immigrants to the [[US]] born in around [[Kraków]] declared themselves as Krakus, Crakowiak, or Bielochrovat (i.e. White Croat) by nationality.{{sfn|United States Immigration commission|1911|pp=22, 40, 43, 88, 105}}

The White Croats contributed and assimilated into Czech, Polish and Ukrainian ethnos.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=131}} Some scholars consider White Croats as the predecessors of the [[Rusyns|Rusyn]] people,{{sfn|Magocsi|1995}}{{sfn|Magocsi|2005|p=5}}{{sfn|Majorov|2012|p=78}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Motta|first=Giuseppe|title=Less than Nations: Central-Eastern European Minorities after WWI, Volumes 1 and 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GnUxBwAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-4438-5859-5|page=156|quote=There were different theories to explain the presence of Rusyns. In his ''The settlements, economy and history of the Rusyns of Subcarpathia'' (1923) A. Hodinka wondered if Russians arrived before the Magyars, at the same time or later? Were they White Croats? Slavs who mixed with nomad Vlachs?}}</ref> particularly [[Lemkos]].{{sfn|Magocsi|2015|p=29}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Katchanovski|first1=Ivan|last2=Kohut|first2=Zenon E.|last3=Nebesio|first3=Bohdan Y.|first4=Myroslav|last4=Yurkevich|title=Historical Dictionary of Ukraine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-h6r57lDC4QC|year=2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7847-1|page=321|quote=In the opinion of some scholars, the ancestors of the Lemkos were the White Croatians, who settled the Carpathian region between the seventh and tenth centuries.}}</ref>

==Legends==
According to Czech and Polish chronicles, the legendary [[Lech, Czech, and Rus|Lech and Czech]] came from (White) Croatia.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=151}} The [[Chronicle of Dalimil]] (14th century) recounts "''V srbském jazyku jest země, jiežto Charvaty jest imě; v téj zemi bieše Lech, jemužto jmě bieše Čech''".{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=151}} [[Alois Jirásek]] recounted as "''Za Tatrami, v rovinách při řece Visle rozkládala se od nepaměti charvátská země, část prvotní veliké vlasti slovanské''" (Behind the [[Tatra Mountains]], in the plains of the river [[Vistula]], stretched from immemorial time Charvátská country ([[White Croatia]]), the initial part of the great Slavic homeland), and ''V té charvátské zemi bytovala četná plemena, příbuzná jazykem, mravy, způsobem života'' (In Charvátská existed numerous tribes, related by language, manners, and way of life).{{sfn|Jirásek|2015}} [[Dušan Třeštík]] noted that the chronicle tells Czech came with six brothers from Croatia which once again indicates seven chiefs/tribes like in the Croatian origo gentis legend from the 30th chapter of ''De Administrando Imperio''.{{sfn|Alimov|2015|pp=153}} It is considered that the chronicle refers to the Carpathian Croatia.{{sfn|Sedov|2012|p=15}}

One of the legendary figures [[Kyi, Shchek and Khoryv]] who founded [[Kiev]], brother Khoryv or Horiv, and its oronym Khorevytsia, is often related to the Croatian ethnonym.{{sfn|Malyckij|2006 (1990)|p=106–107}}{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=99–102, 109}} This legend, recorded by Nestor, has similar Armenian transcript from the 7th-8th century, in which Horiv is mentioned as ''Horean''.{{sfn|Malyckij|2006 (1990)|p=107}} Paščenko related his name, beside to the Croatian ethnonym, to solar deity [[Deities of Slavic religion#Sun-god and moon-god|Hors]].{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=99–102, 109}} Near Kiev there's a stream where previously existed large homonymous village Horvatka or Hrovatka (destroyed in the time of [[Joseph Stalin]]), which flows into [[Stuhna River]].{{sfn|Strižak|2006 (1990)|p=106–107}} In the vicinity are parts of the [[Serpent's Wall]].{{sfn|Strižak|2006 (1990)|p=187}}

Scholars consider that Croats could have been mentioned in the Old English and Nordic epic poems. The verse in Old English poem ''[[Widsith]]'' (10th century):

{|style="border: 0px" align=center cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0
|-
| |''Wulfhere sohte ic ond Wyrmhere; ful oft þær wig ne alæg,'' 
| |I visited Wulfhere and Wyrmhere; there battle often raged,
|-
| |''þonne Hræda here heardum sweordum,'' 
| | when the Hræda with their sharp swords,
|-
| |''ymb Wistlawudu wergan sceoldon'' 
| |  in the [[Vistula]] woods had to defend
|-
| |''ealdne eþelstol Ætlan leodum.'' 
| | their ancestral seat against [[Attila]]'s host.
|}

The Hræda is genitive plural of *''Hraede'', and is usually related with the [[Goths]] (''Hred-Gotum'', ''Hreth-Gotan'', ''Hreidhgotar'').{{sfn|Lewicki|2006 (1951)|p=95}} However, this verse is similar to the one in [[Hervarar saga ok Heiðreks]] (13th century), where prior the battle between Goths and Huns, [[Heidrek]] died in ''Harvaða fjöllum'' (Carpathian Mountains{{sfn|Pendergrass|2015|p=75}}{{sfn|Shippey|2014|p=53}}) which is sometimes translated as "beneath the mountains of Harvathi", considered somewhere beneath Carpathian Mountains near river Dnieper.{{sfn|Lewicki|2006 (1951)|p=95}}{{sfn|Acker|Larrington|2013|p=245}}{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=96}} Lewicki argued that [[Anglo-Saxons]], as in the case of Alfred the Great where called Croats ''Horithi'', often distorted foreign Slavic names.{{sfn|Lewicki|2006 (1951)|p=95–96}}

The legendary Czech hermit from the 9th century, Svatý Ivan, is mentioned as the son of certain king Gestimul or Gostimysl, who according to the Czech chronicles descended from the Croats or [[Obotrites]].{{sfn|Vašica|2008 (1935)|p=242, 244, 247–248, 250–258}}

